{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e558a537-1856-43da-a577-b6637e5427ba","content":"Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Activated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Event order (typical):**\n\n| Transition | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | Created → Activated → Resumed |\n| Sent to background | Deactivated → Stopped → Backgrounding |\n| Brought back | Resumed → Activated |\n| App closed | Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying |\n\n> `Backgrounding` is iOS/Mac Catalyst only — use it to save state. On Android/Windows it won't fire.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f9153cb0-beeb-4f23-8096-716f1ec8acdc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to subscribe to Window lifecycle events in a .NET MAUI app for debugging/logging purposes. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI that I can answer directly without needing to look at any codebase.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `Window` class exposes several lifecycle events that correspond to the app's state transitions. Let me provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":441,"requestId":"080A:187D22:A1FCBB:BBE4A7:69F2A87C"},"id":"d423fb1a-06ac-45f9-a6bc-1c5196e16cc5","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:55:33.200Z","parentId":"230dcfe0-9333-4f2c-af57-73f26e68a9a6"}
